YELLOW FEVER - AFRICA (22): SUDAN (DARFUR)
******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Thu 22 Nov 2012
Source: Akhirlahza [in Arabic, trans. Corr.SB, edited]
http://www.akhirlahza.sd/akhir/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=22816


[This report is from one of the main Arabic language newspapers in Sudan. The initial part of the report gives incidence figures that are somewhat lower than those from reports over the past 3 days (see ProMED-mail archives below), so will not be given here. New information follows. - Mod.TY]

Ahmed Ishaq Yaqoub, Minister of Health in West Darfur, pointed to the arrival of 35 mounted spray pump machines mounted [presumably on vehicles? Corr.SB] and a federal health and blood bank equipment worth over one million [Sudanese pounds; USD 225 000]. The Minister of Health in South Darfur, Ahmed Al-Tayeb, said that the disease is spreading to new areas of the state and new cases must be expected. He pointed out that intensive efforts are under way to combat and trap mosquitoes which transmit the disease. The good news is that a conference [was held?] in Nyala on Monday (Nyala had recorded 2 cases in southern and northern areas of the State) and a programme of education and Health is being undertaken to inform the public about the dangers of the disease.

Newspaper sources state that about 10 000 workers in the gold mines fled to Nyala after the spread of yellow fever in the mining areas of Jebel Amer. This has created concern and tension among the citizens in Nyala with the possibility of transferring the infection to the cities with the event of carriers of this disease. The sources added that the mining area had more than 60 cases. A prospector, with family, said some miners had come from the neighboring countries of Chad and the Central African Republic. The spread of the disease in South Darfur is a disaster and the epidemic requires organizations and the international community to address the disease and provide enough vaccines to vaccinate all citizens of the state, especially to [be provided to] the Nyala Teaching Hospital where many of the patients in critically ill condition are being treated. The referral hospital for the states of Central and Southern Darfur is in a deplorable state from the accumulation of hundreds of patients, some sleeping on the ground outside, lack of medical staff, and acute shortage of medical equipment.

Observers fear of the spread of the disease to the south side of South Darfur state with the nomadic movement that started from the north (of Darfur). It is important to provide vaccines that protect all the citizens of the state from this incurable disease.

[Byline: Mahad Mohamed Khair]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Re "...vaccinate all citizens of the state, especially to [be provided to] the Nyala Teaching Hospital where many of the patients in critically ill condition are being treated...": the medical and nursing staff at that hospital were reportedly vaccinated on Tue 20 Nov 2012, so will be protected by the end of the month. Vaccination cannot help inpatients.

Re "...some miners had come from the neighboring countries of Chad and the Central African Republic..." If there is already YF in the mining camps, miners fleeing back to those countries rather than to Nyala will pose a threat to those countries.

Map of Sudan showing Jebel Marra in the west central part of the country:
http://dianabuja.files.wordpress.com/2009/09/www-everyculture-com-map2.jpg?w=584
Map of Jebel Marra showing Nertiti and Zalingei on road west to Chad:
