******
[2]
Date: Thu 22 Nov 2012
Source: Radio Dabanga [edited]
http://www.radiodabanga.org/node/38701


West Darfur
-----------
The death toll as a result of the yellow fever epidemic in West Darfur has risen to 47, while the total number of infections reached a number of 157, Radio Dabanga learned on Wednesday 21 Nov [2012].

Ahmed Ishaq Yaqoub, West Darfur's Health Minister, told Radio Dabanga that 2 people passed away on Wednesday [21 Nov 2012] as a result of the fever, thus bringing the death toll to 47. He added that the state of West Darfur did not experience any issues with the vaccines so far; however, he claimed that some of the centers remain empty due to the remote location.

The minister explained that the campaign will continue for 11 more days, which he considers to be sufficient for vaccinating all citizens in West Darfur's 4 localities. Yaqoub announced that all schools in the state have been visited and all pupils have been vaccinated in the meantime.

West Darfur's health minister added that he visited the localities of Foro Baranga and Habila on Wednesday [21 Nov 2012] to check the conditions of the hospitals and to ensure that all patients are received and vaccinated. [Vaccinating individuals who are ill with yellow fever virus infections is not effective treatment because the vaccination comes too late. If the statement means that well individuals are being vaccinated at the hospital, that is a preventive measure. - Mod.TY]

He appealed to the citizens in the affected localities to go to the vaccination centers.

North Darfur
------------
At the same time, Abu al-Abbas Abdullah al-Tayyeb, North Darfur's Health Minister, told Radio Dabanga that 250 000 doses of the vaccine have arrived in the state. He claims this is not sufficient to cover all the affected areas, adding in a press statement that the vaccines will be distributed to the localities adjacent to the regions where the disease is still spreading.

The minister announced that the vaccination campaign will start on Wednesday [21 Nov 2012] and will continue for 12 days in the localities of Sreif and Saraf Omra, he added to Radio Dabanga.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The stated lack of sufficient YF vaccine, and the relatively brief time allocated for application (11-12 days), considering the large geographic area and scattered cases within it, are a cause for serious concern. Adequate surveillance to promptly detect new cases in new locations is also a significant challenge in the Darfur states. The reports above indicate that spraying is an additional measure to halt transmission. As noted in previous comments, this will provide only temporary mosquito vector control if not accompanied by elimination of breeding sites. - Mod.TY

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/3EpA.]
